Andrew is building a scale model of an elephant. He determines that a real elephant is 10 feet tall and 14 feet long. If Andrew wants his model to be 8 inches tall, how many inches long should his model be?

}

\textbf{Answer:} We begin by setting up the proportion $\dfrac{\text{height of real elephant}}{\text{length of real elephant}} = \dfrac{\text{height of model}}{\text{length of model}}$. Letting $x$ be the length of the model in inches and plugging in the information from the problem, we have $\dfrac{10\;\cancel{\text{feet}}}{14\;\cancel{\text{feet}}} = \dfrac{8\;\cancel{\text{inches}}}{x\;\cancel{\text{inches}}}$. Multiplying each side by $14x$, we have\begin{align*}
10x = 14\times 8 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad 10x = 112 \\
\Rightarrow\quad x = \boxed{11.2}.
\end{align*}
}
